editorialSummary.text: Longtime Village restaurant serves pub fare & brunch in an unpretentious setting.

originalText.text:
Tavern like vibes inside and it seems old school but the service is just fantastic.

Food is great! Ordered the burger and I typically prefer smash burgers but this may top that now. The burger itself wasn’t too dense so it was easy to eat and not overly chewy. 10/10 burger which I also added cheese.

My favorite style of fries as well but I’m tryna find out what style it is!

originalText.text: I have enjoyed every entree that I have eaten here, all the flavors were on point ( Burgers,  chicken, salmon). The ice cream sundae was excellent quality ice cream and the whipped cream/hot fudge was fresh. The carrot cake was fresh, moist, the texture was not my preference, overall it was just okay. Our server was top notch: delightful, helpful and patient-I wish I could recall the older gentleman's name. The quaint/intimate atmosphere was enjoyable as well. It's clear this restaurant knows what it is doing, it makes you want to return.

originalText.text: A great place with a neighborly vibe. Many of the customers know the waiters by name. One waiter has been working there since the early 1970s. Most items on the menu are good, as are the specials. The hamburgers are amongst the best in NYC, in my humble opinion. The desserts are excellent as well.

originalText.text: I love this excellent West Village joint. The food is excellent and ambiance is  good, but nothing to write home about. The main reason I go there is the friendly staff. 5 of us went there for breakfast and it wasn't prohibitive. Not like West Village real estate!! The omelet was pretty good. I had an avocado toast which was pretty good. Overall the service was good. Not super fast and so it gave us a lot of time to relax and spend a lazy weekend morning over breakfast.

originalText.text:
~ Appetizers~
We ordered the calamari which was served with a curry aioli so addictive we wanted to bring a bucket full home; and a plate of marinated shrimp dressed in a vibrant, citrusy vinaigrette that was zesty yet balanced.
~ Mains ~
TRY: The Grilled Shrimp with ginger-lime sauce and the sliced steak with Merlot-ginger sauce.
SKIP: The spaghettini served with goat cheese, arugula, olives, capers, sundried tomatoes, and tomato sauce. As tantalizing that this sounded, the dish fell flat and failed to impress; the ingredients felt out of harmony with each other.
~ Dessert ~
TRY: Scarlett O’Hara’s Coffee Cantata – globes of coffee ice cream served with raspberries, hot fudge; this came with an off-puttingly extravagant amount of whipped cream but was delicious overall!
SKIP: Vienna Woods – crepe filled with hot fudge, hazelnuts, and whipped cream; a generic crepe that was cloying (too much whipped cream) and one-dimensional.

We absolutely loved the ambience of the place, and the cozy, intimate interiors. Note, though, that the dining area is not the most spacious and you might end up rubbing shoulders with other patrons. Will be back to sample more of their menu!
